u}(n):=\sum_{d\mid n}d^{
u}$, and $q := e^{2\pi i 	au}$. If $k \geq 4$, then $E_k(	au)$ is a weight $k$ holomorphic modular form on $\SL_2(\Z)$. Rankin and Swinnerton-Dyer \cite{RSD} showed that the zeros of these series lie on the lower boundary of the standard fundamental domain $\mathcal{F}$ for $\SL_2(\Z),$ the arc of the unit circle  egin{equation} \label{A} \mathcal{A}:= \left \{ 	au \in \H \ : \ |	au|=1\ \ {	ext {m with}}\ \ - rac{1}{2}\leq e(	au)\leq 0 ight\}. \end{equation} This result may be stated in terms of ``divisor polynomials'' of modular forms, with zeros in the interval $[0, 1728]$. Viewed in this lens, we observe similar phenomena in the zeros of polynomials arising from other forms on $\SL_2(\Z)$, including meromorphic Poincar'e series \cite{Rankin} and images of the $j$-function under the Hecke action \cite{AKN}. Here, we expand this picture to include a large class of harmonic Maass forms, generalizing work of Ono and the author \cite{GomezOno}. Namely, for weak Hecke eigenforms $F$ of weight $2-k$ with real Fourier coefficients, we define Hecke polynomials $P_n(F;x)$ and prove that, for large $n$, all of their zeros are simple and lie in $[0,1728]$, and that these zeros equidistribute as $n 	o \infty$. Our method expresses $F$ as a linear combination of Maass–Poincar'e series and tracks Hecke action along the arc $\cA$. To state these results, define $$ \widetilde{E}_k(	au):= egin{cases} 1 \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 0\pmod{12},\ E_{4}(z)^2E_6(z) \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 2\pmod{12},\ E_4(z)\ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 4\pmod{12},\ E_6(z)\ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 6\pmod{12},\ E_4(z)^2\ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 8\pmod{12},\ E_{4}(z)E_6(z) \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 10\pmod{12}. \end{cases} $$ We also recall the classical modular discriminant $$ \Delta(	au)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} 	au(n)q^n:= rac{E_4(	au)^3-E_6(	au)^2}{1728}=q-24q^2+252q^3-\cdots, $$ and the modular $j$-invariant $$ j(	au):= rac{E_4(	au)^3}{\Delta(	au)}=q^{-1}+744+196884q+\cdots. $$ We may then construct the Hecke polynomials $P_n(F;x)$.  egin{theorem}\label{Theorem1} Suppose that $F(	au) = \sum_{l=-m}^{\infty} c_F^+(l)q^l = q^{-m} + O(q^{-m+1})$ is a weight $2 - k$ harmonic Maass weak eigenform with real Fourier coefficients with shadow $G(	au) = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a(n)q^n$. Then the following are true. 
oindent (1) For every $n \geq 2$, we have that $$ H_n(F;	au) := \Delta(	au)^{b(k - 2)} \widetilde{E}_{k-2}(	au) \cdot \left( n^{k-1} F(	au) \ | \ T_{2-k}(n) - a(n)F(	au) ight) $$ is a weakly holomorphic function on $\SL_2(\Z)$, where $$ b(k):= egin{cases} \lfloor k/12floor \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {if}}\ k
ot \equiv 2\pmod{12},\ \lfloor k/12floor -1 \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {if}}\ k\equiv 2\pmod{12}. \end{cases} $$ 
oindent (2) For every $n \geq 2$, there exists a monic polynomial $P_n(F;x) \in \R[x]$ of degree $mn - b(k - 2)$ for which $$ P_n(F;j(	au)) = H_n(F;	au). $$ \end{theorem} These polynomials, by their construction,  egin{theorem} \label{Theorem2} Assuming the notations and hypotheses of Theorem~ef{Theorem1}, if $n \geq 7$ satisfies $$ C_F n^{k-1} e^{-\pi n rac{\sqrt{3}}{2}} < 1, $$ then $P_n(F;x)$ has $mn - b(k - 2)$ distinct zeros in $[0,1728]$, where $$ C_F :=  rac{1}{4}\max \left\{80m^{k-1}\sum_{l=1}^{m} \abs{c_F^+(-l)}, 1ight\} $$ is a constant depending only on $F$. \end{theorem}  egin{remark} Moreover, we have that the zeros of $P_n(F;x)$ include $0$ (resp. $1728$) for $n$ satisfying the hypotheses of Theorem~ef{Theorem2} if $k \equiv 2,4 \pmod{6}$ (resp. $k \equiv 2 \pmod{4}$). \end{remark} We also obtain equistribution of these zeros.  egin{corollary}\label{Corollary3} Assuming the notation and hypotheses of Theorem~ef{Theorem1}, then for sufficiently large $n$, we have that the zeros of $P_n(F;x)$ are distinct and equidistributed in the interval $[0, 1728]$. \end{corollary} This paper is organized as follows. In Section 2, we discuss previous work concerning zeros of forms on $\SL_2(\Z)$ and recall necessary background on harmonic Maass forms. We prove Theorem~ef{Theorem1} in Section 3 using the theory of Hecke operators for harmonic Maass forms. Finally, in Section 4, we recall and prove useful facts about Maass-Poincar'e series and use these to prove Theorem~ef{Theorem2}. \section*{Acknowledgements} The author thanks Ken Ono for very helpful guidance and comments in the writing of this manuscript. \section{Background and Notation} Theorems~ef{Theorem1} and~ef{Theorem2} are motivated by an array of similar results concerning the zeros of forms on $\SL_2(\Z)$. We begin with the theorem of Rankin and Swinnerton-Dyer, which in this context may be stated as follows. Given a modular form $f(	au)$ of weight $k$, define $$ \widetilde{P}(f; j(	au)) =  rac{f(	au)}{\Delta(	au)^{b(k)}\widetilde{E}_k(	au)}. $$ Since the $\widetilde{E}_k(	au)$ capture exactly the trivial zeros of $f(	au)$, $\widetilde{P}(f; j(	au))$ is holomorphic on the upper half-plane. By dividing by the appropriate power of $\Delta(	au)$, we have a weakly holomorphic modular function (i.e. its poles are supported at the cusp at $\infty$). Because the $j$-function is a bijection from $\cF$ to $\C$, it follows that $\widetilde{P}(f; j(	au))$ is a polynomial in $j(	au)$. After noting that $j(i)=1728$ and $j(\omega)=0$, and then setting $$ h_k(x):= egin{cases} 1 \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 0\pmod{12},\ x^2(x-1728) \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 2\pmod{12},\ x \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 4\pmod{12},\ x-1728 \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 6\pmod{12},\ x^2 \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 8\pmod{12},\ x(x-1728) \ \ \ \ \ &{	ext {m if}}\ k\equiv 10\pmod{12}, \end{cases} $$ 
oindent we obtain the {\it divisor polynomial} of $f(	au)$ by  egin{equation*} P(f;x) = h_k(x)\cdot \widetilde{P}(f;x). \end{equation*} Since $j : \mathcal{A}\mapsto [0, 1728]$, the theorem of Rankin and Swinnerton-Dyer asserts that the zeros of $F(E_{2k};x)$ are in the interval $[0, 1728]$. Proceeding similarly, the zeros of certain meromorphic Poincar'e series may also be pinpointed to the arc $\cA$ \cite{Rankin}. The same phenomenon was discovered by Asai, Kaneko, and Ninomiya \cite{AKN} in connection with the Hecke operators $T_0(n)$ acting on the modular $j$-function. To describe their result, we recall an important sequence of modular functions. Let $j_0(	au):=1$, and for every positive integer $n$, and let $j_n(	au)$ be the unique modular function which is holomorphic on $\H$ whose $q$-expansion satisfies $$ j_n(	au)=q^{-n}+\sum_{l=1}^{\infty}c_n(l)q^l. $$ Each $j_n(	au)$ is a monic degree $n$ integer polynomial $J_n(x)$ for $x=j(	au)$. We refer to these expressions as ``Hecke polynomials'', as they satisfy $$ J_n(j(	au))=j_n(	au)= n(j_1(	au) \ | \ T_0(n)). $$ Asai, Kaneko, and Ninomiya proved that the zeros of $J_n(x) \in \Z[x]$ are simple and lie in $[0, 1728]$. This was accomplished by showing that the $J_n(x)$'s are well-approximated by a damped cosine wave for all $n \geq 2$, which also demonstrates that the zeros are equidistributed in $[0, 1728]$ for $n$ sufficiently large. Recently, in further pursuit of this phenomenon, Ono and the author \cite{GomezOno} proved an analogous result for the sequence of Hecke polynomials arising from the special weight $-10$ 	extit{harmonic Maass form} $$ R(	au) := M_\Delta(	au) + N_\Delta(	au). $$ Here $N_\Delta(	au)$ is the nonholomorphic period integral function $$ N_{\Delta}(	au) = (2\pi)^{11}\cdot 11i\cdot  eta_{\Delta}\int_{-\overline{	au}}^{i \infty}  rac{\overline{\Delta(-\overline{z})}}{(-i(z+	au))^{-10}} \ dz $$ arising from the modular discriminant, with $ eta_\Delta$ an explicit real constant, and $M_\Delta(	au)$ is the mock modular form  egin{equation*}  egin{split} M_{\Delta}(	au)&=\sum_{n=-1}^{\infty}\ad(n)q^n=11!\cdot q^{-1}+ rac{24\cdot 11!}{B_{12}}-73562460235.684\dots q -929026615019.113\dots q^2 - \cdots. \end{split} \end{equation*} The coefficients $a_\Delta(	au)$ are given by absolutely convergent infinite series  egin{equation*} \ad(n)=-2\pi\Gamma(12)n^{- rac{11}{2}}\cdot \sum_{c=1}^{\infty} rac{K(-1,n,c)}{c}\cdot I_{11}\left( rac{4\pi \sqrt{n}}{c} ight), \end{equation*} where $I_{11}(x)$ is the usual $I_{11}$-Bessel function and $K(m,n,c)$ is the Kloosterman sum  egin{equation} \label{Kloosterman} K(m,n,c):= \sum_{v(c)^{	imes}} e\left( rac{m\overline v+nv}{c}ight), \end{equation} where $v$ runs over the primitive residue classes modulo $c$, and $\overline v$ is the multiplicative inverse of $v$. For background on harmonic Maass forms and their applications, the reader can see \cite{BOAnnals, BOInventiones, BOPNAS, BOR, Br, BF, BruinierOno, OnoCDM, OnoMock}. As seen from their construction (see \cite{OnoMock}), $M_\Delta(	au)$ and $N_\Delta(	au)$ are intrinsically related to the modular discriminant. Indeed, the action of the weight $-10$ Hecke operator on $N_\Delta(	au)$ is essentially the weight $12$ Hecke action on $\Delta(	au)$, which we explicate concretely as follows. Let $	au := u + iv$. Recall that if $F(	au)$ is a harmonic Maass form of even weight $2 - k$, then it has a Fourier expansion of the form (for example, see Lemma 4.2 of \cite{HMF}) $$ F(	au) = \sum_{n \gg -\infty} c_F^+(n)q^n + \sum_{n < 0} c_F^-(n) \gamma(k - 1, -4\pi nv)q^n, $$ where $$ \Gamma(s,z) := \int_z^\infty e^{-t} t^s  rac{dt}{t} $$ is the incomplete gamma function. The $q$-series $$ F^+(	au) := \sum_{n \gg -\infty} c_F^+(n)q^n $$ is the 	extit{holomorphic part} of $F(	au)$, while its 	extit{nonholomorphic part} is $$ F^-(	au) := \sum_{n < 0} c_F^-(n) \gamma(k - 1, -4\pi nv)q^n. $$ In the case of $R(	au)$, we have that $F^+(	au) = M_\Delta(	au)$ and $F^-(	au) = N_\Delta(	au)$. We also recall the differential operator $$ \xi_k := 2iv^k \overline{ rac{\partial}{\partial \overline{	au}}}. $$ Following from the work Bruinier and Funke (see Proposition 3.2 of \cite{BF} and Theorem 5.9 of \cite{HMF}), the $\xi$-operator captures succinctly how we may relate a given cusp form to a corresponding infinite family of harmonic Maass forms. If $F(	au)$ is a harmonic Maass form of weight $2 - k$, then $\xi_{2-k}(F(	au))$ is a holomorphic cusp form of weight $k$, which we refer to as the 	extit{shadow} of $F^+(	au)$. Its Fourier expansion is given explicitly by (for example, see Theorem 5.9 of \cite{HMF})  egin{equation} \label{HeckeXi} \xi_{2-k}(F(	au)) = \xi_{2-k}(F^-(	au)) = -(4\pi)^{k-1} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \overline{c_F^-(-n)}n^{k-1}q^n. \end{equation} For the case of $ R(	au)$, we have that $\xi_{-10}(R(	au)) = -11 eta_{\Delta} \cdot \Delta(	au)$. Using the commutation relation (see Lemma 2.2 of \cite{GomezOno}) $$ \xi_{2-k}(F(	au) \ | \ T_{2-k}(n)) = \xi_{2-k}(F(	au)) \ | \ T_k(n), $$ Ono and the author are able to construct a weight zero form with vanishing nonholomorphic part arising from $M_{\Delta}(	au)$, and thus obtain a sequence of polynomials $\{P_n(R;x) \colon n \geq 2\}$ given by the relation $$ P_n(R;j(	au)) =  rac{E_4(	au)E_6(	au)}{11!} \cdot \left(n^{11} M_\Delta(	au) \ | \ T_{-10}(n) - 	au(n)M_\Delta(	au)ight). $$ For all $n \geq 2$, the zeros of these polynomials are simple and are in $[0,1728]$. Furthermore, as $n 	o \infty$, these zeroes become equidistributed within $[0,1728]$. The case of $R(	au)$ extends readily to all 	extit{weak Hecke eigenforms} $F$; that is, weight $2-k$ harmonic Maass forms with real Fourier coefficients whose shadows are weight $k$ Hecke eigenforms. We mirror the methods in \cite{GomezOno} to show that $H_n(F;	au)$ is a weight zero form with vanishing nonholomorphic part, and that the Hecke action along $\cA$ may be analyzed explicitly by realizing $H_n(F;	au)$ as a linear combination of Maass-Poincar'